WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:06.300
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:06.300 --> 00:00:09.170
&gt;&gt; Michael: Ladies and gentlemen,
please welcome the 14th Librarian

00:00:09.170 --> 00:00:12.050
of Congress, Doctor
Carla Hayden [applause].

00:00:14.880 --> 00:00:17.570 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: Thank you, Michael.

00:00:17.570 --> 00:00:21.320
I don't know about you, but I am
having a great time [applause,

00:00:21.320 --> 00:00:25.240
cheering].

00:00:25.240 --> 00:00:28.690
Welcome to the Library of
Congress National Book Festival,

00:00:28.690 --> 00:00:30.640
our premiere public event.

00:00:30.640 --> 00:00:36.370
And this is my first book
festival, officiating [applause].

00:00:38.090 --> 00:00:41.740
And, as you can see, I am
pretty thrilled to be here.

00:00:41.740 --> 00:00:46.920
Now today is our, and it's an honor
for me to be able to say "our",

00:00:46.920 --> 00:00:50.370
16th annual celebration
of books and reading.

00:00:50.370 --> 00:00:53.310
And, as you can see from
the beautiful art behind me

00:00:53.310 --> 00:00:54.750
and throughout the
convention center,

00:00:54.750 --> 00:00:58.250
the theme of this year's
festival is Journeys,

00:00:58.250 --> 00:01:00.450
because books really do take us

00:01:00.450 --> 00:01:05.660
on journeys we might not,
otherwise, ever go on.

00:01:05.660 --> 00:01:08.360
They make us think about
the world we live in,

00:01:08.360 --> 00:01:11.560
and also the one that preceded us.

00:01:11.560 --> 00:01:15.120
They are our portals
into the future.

00:01:15.120 --> 00:01:21.020
As Thomas Jefferson once said,
"I cannot live without books".

00:01:21.020 --> 00:01:26.610
I have been a librarian my entire
career and I could not agree more.

00:01:26.610 --> 00:01:29.010
And I would take a bet that
there are a lot of people

00:01:29.010 --> 00:01:30.810
in this room who would agree too.

00:01:30.810 --> 00:01:39.040
[ Applause ]

00:01:39.040 --> 00:01:47.560
I would like to invite a person who
has made this festival possible.

00:01:47.560 --> 00:01:51.330
I am pleased to bring to the
stage Mister David Rubenstein

00:01:51.330 --> 00:01:55.180
who will be interviewing our
exciting guest and author.

00:01:55.180 --> 00:01:58.650
I would dare to say
that no one cares more

00:01:58.650 --> 00:02:00.350 position:56%
about books and literacy than David.

00:02:00.350 --> 00:02:03.520
And we cannot thank him
enough for his support

00:02:03.520 --> 00:02:06.510
of the National Book
Festival every year.

00:02:06.510 --> 00:02:13.190
[ Applause ]

00:02:13.190 --> 00:02:18.020 position:56%
And, thanks to his generosity, I am
able to announce today that the date

00:02:18.020 --> 00:02:21.280
of next year's National
Book Festival will be

00:02:21.280 --> 00:02:23.820
on Saturday, September 2nd.

00:02:23.820 --> 00:02:26.120
So mark your calendars [applause].

00:02:28.400 --> 00:02:34.250
David is a wonderful and
experienced interviewer,

00:02:34.250 --> 00:02:36.690
and I know you are looking forward

00:02:36.690 --> 00:02:39.330
to his conversation
for his special guest.

00:02:39.330 --> 00:02:42.580
I am too because I get
to sit down and listen.

00:02:42.580 --> 00:02:44.880
&gt;&gt; David Rubenstein:
Okay, thank you.

00:02:49.120 --> 00:02:51.740
So, [applause] country is very
fortunate to have a Librarian

00:02:51.740 --> 00:02:57.930
of Congress from my
hometown of Baltimore and,

00:02:57.930 --> 00:03:00.450
[applause] for several
hundred years, we managed never

00:03:00.450 --> 00:03:03.260
to have a female Librarian
of Congress.

00:03:03.260 --> 00:03:05.060
That's now been corrected.

00:03:05.060 --> 00:03:11.050
[ Applause, Cheering ]

00:03:11.050 --> 00:03:15.350
And for several hundred years, we
never had a person of color serve

00:03:15.350 --> 00:03:16.650
as Librarian of Congress.

00:03:16.650 --> 00:03:22.880
That's now been corrected
[applause, cheering].

00:03:22.880 --> 00:03:24.950
So, Carla, everybody is
looking forward to your tenure

00:03:24.950 --> 00:03:29.010
and congratulations on this
position and thank you very much

00:03:29.010 --> 00:03:35.360 position:56%
for taking this position [applause].

00:03:35.360 --> 00:03:38.590
So we have a special treat today.

00:03:38.590 --> 00:03:43.600
Somebody who is, I would say, the
most dominant person in television.

00:03:43.600 --> 00:03:48.660
What she has done is something
that nobody had done really before.

00:03:48.660 --> 00:03:55.830
Now in a profession that is
typically dominated by white males,

00:03:55.830 --> 00:03:57.830
she has been the dominant figure.

00:03:57.830 --> 00:04:02.070 position:56%
And that is in television
production and creation and writing.

00:04:02.070 --> 00:04:08.170
And she has written more
top television shows

00:04:08.170 --> 00:04:10.480
and produced more top
television shows

00:04:10.480 --> 00:04:13.800
than anybody currently,
anybody in history.

00:04:13.800 --> 00:04:18.500
Shonda Rhimes is a person who grew
up in Chicago, went to Dartmouth,

00:04:18.500 --> 00:04:20.690
went to University of
Southern California,

00:04:20.690 --> 00:04:25.160
and then began writing
screenplays for movies.

